The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, July 25: The government today set Rs 270-290 as the price band for the follow-on public offer of state-run Engineer India Ltd. A group of ministers, headed by finance minister Pranab Mukherjee, set the price band at a discount to Fridays closing of Rs 337.65 for the sale of the governments 10 per cent shareholding in the firm. The government will raise about Rs 9,000 crore at the lower end of the price band and over Rs 9,700 crore at the upper end, official sources said. EILs offer of 33.69 million equity shares will open on July 27 and close on July 29 for qualified institutional buyers and on July 30 for the rest (retail and HNIs).                             
	 Mumbai, July 25: The government is open to infusing more equity into Air India provided the national carrier improves its performance. The airline is on the recovery path with the average revenue rising by Rs 638 crore in the first quarter of 2010, Patel said. There are also no plans to either reduce manpower or slash salaries of around 30,000 employees of Air India.                            
	 New Delhi, July 25: Finance minister Pranab Mukherjee today asked regional rural banks (RRBs) to introduce revised pay structure for their employees on a par with PSU banks from November 1, 2007, which will cost them Rs 791 crore on arrears payment and plunge more of them into losses. The additional cost will bring down the total profits of the RRBs from Rs 2,374 crore during 2009-10.                            
	 London, July 25: Citigroup, the Bank of America and 15 other bailed-out financial services companies overpaid their top executives by $1.6 billion during the height of the financial crisis, a review by the US government on top executives compensation has found.                             
	 New Delhi, July 25: The BSE is looking for alliances with some regional stock exchanges to increase its footprint in the country. It is in talks with some of the bourses, BSE deputy CEO Ashish Chauhan said.                             
	 New Delhi, July 25: SAILs 20 per cent share sale plan, which aims to generate up to Rs 16,000 crore, may not happen this calendar year because of regulatory hurdles.                                                                                                                          
